          "body": "Verses 7-10 are the chapter's pastoral heartbeat — seven positive imperatives issued without apology. Go. Eat. Drink. Let your clothes be white. Let oil not be lacking. Enjoy life with the woman whom you love. Do with all your might. These commands are remarkable in a book best known for its dark realism. What warrants them? Two grounds are given explicitly. First, **God has already approved your works** (9:7) — the divine *ratsah* (approval, pleasure, acceptance) has been declared over the life of the one being addressed. This is not earned by exceptional performance; it is the prior acceptance that licenses the enjoyment. Second, this enjoyment is **your portion** (*cheleq*, 9:9) — a gift-word that appears in both 9:6 (the dead have no portion) and 9:9 (this is your portion). The gift is the counterpoint to the loss. The white garments and the oil on the head (9:8) are ancient symbols of festivity and celebration — worn at weddings and banquets, not at funerals. The Preacher is not prescribing hedonism but commanding the concrete inhabiting of ordinary life. Verse 10 delivers the chapter's most urgent imperative: whatever your hand finds to do, do it with **all your might** (*koach*), because Sheol is coming and there is no activity there. This is not fear-driven frantic productivity; it is the full engagement of one who knows the window is open and refuses to waste it."
